<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<h4 style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;page-break-after:auto;text-autospace:none;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Item 8.01.&#160; Other Events.</font></b></h4>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Filed
as part of this Current Report on Form 8-K are the consolidated balance sheets
of Kraft Foods Inc. and subsidiaries as of December&nbsp;31, 2004 and 2003, and
the related consolidated statements of earnings, stockholders&#146; equity and cash
flows for each of the three years in the period ended December&nbsp;31, 2004
(the &#147;Financial Statements&#148;), the independent registered public accounting
firm&#146;s report thereon and the statement regarding computation of ratios of
earnings to fixed charges.&#160; The Financial
Statements and the independent registered public accounting firm&#146;s report will
be incorporated by reference in Kraft Foods Inc.&#146;s Annual Report on Form 10-K
for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2004.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<h4 style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;page-break-after:auto;text-autospace:none;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Item 9.01.&#160; Financial Statements
and Exhibits.</font></b></h4>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

Financial Statements, together with the independent registered public
accounting firm&#146;s report thereon, are included herein.</font></p>

  <td width="0%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:.98%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
 <tr>
  <td width="62%" valign="top" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:62.4%;">

<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div style="font-family:Times New Roman;">

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">KRAFT FOODS INC. and
SUBSIDIARIES</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">NOTES to CONSOLIDATED FINANCIAL
STATEMENTS</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;page-break-after:auto;text-decoration:underline;"><u><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Note 1.&#160; Background and Basis of Presentation:</font></u></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:9.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Background:</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Kraft Foods Inc. (&#147;Kraft&#148;) was incorporated in 2000 in the Commonwealth
of Virginia.&#160; Kraft, through its
subsidiaries (Kraft and its subsidiaries are hereinafter referred to as the &#147;Company&#148;),
is engaged in the manufacture and sale of branded foods and beverages in the
United States, Canada, Europe, Latin America, Asia Pacific and Middle East and
Africa.</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Prior to June&nbsp;13, 2001, the Company was a wholly-owned subsidiary
of Altria Group, Inc.&#160; On June&nbsp;13,
2001, the Company completed an initial public offering (&#147;IPO&#148;) of 280,000,000
shares of its Class A common stock at a price of $31.00 per share.&#160; At December&nbsp;31, 2004, Altria Group, Inc.
held 98.0% of the combined voting power of the Company&#146;s outstanding capital
stock and owned 85.4% of the outstanding shares of the Company&#146;s capital stock.</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">On November&nbsp;15, 2004, the Company announced the sale of
substantially all of its sugar confectionery business for approximately $1.5
billion.&#160; The transaction, which is
subject to regulatory approval, is expected to be completed in the second
quarter of 2005.&#160; The Company has reflected
the results of its sugar confectionery business as discontinued operations on
the consolidated statements of earnings for all years presented.&#160; The assets related to the sugar confectionery
business were reflected as assets of discontinued operations held for sale on
the consolidated balance sheet at December&nbsp;31, 2004.&#160; Accordingly, historical statements of
earnings amounts included in the notes to the consolidated financial statements
have been restated to reflect the discontinued operation.</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">During January&nbsp;2004,
the Company announced a new global organization structure, which resulted in
new segments.&#160; During the fourth quarter
of 2004, following the sale of its sugar confectionery business, </font>the Company realigned its North American
segments.&#160; The Company&#146;s new segments,
which are reflected in these financial statements and notes, are U.S.
Beverages; U.S. Cheese, Canada &amp; North America Foodservice; U.S. Convenient
Meals; U.S. Grocery; U.S. Snacks &amp; Cereals; Europe, Middle East &amp;
Africa; and Latin America &amp; Asia Pacific.&#160;
The new segment structure in North America reflects a shift of certain
divisions and brands between segments to more closely align these businesses to
consumer sectors, to provide more focus on the separate beverage and grocery
businesses, and to benefit from synergies in grain based products.&#160; Historical data have been restated to reflect
the new segment structure.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:9.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Basis of
presentation:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The
consolidated financial statements include Kraft, as well as its wholly-owned
and majority-owned subsidiaries.&#160;
Investments in which the Company exercises significant influence (20% -
50% ownership interest) are accounted for under the equity method of
accounting.&#160; Investments in which the
Company has an ownership interest of less than 20%, or does not exercise
significant influence, are accounted for with the cost method of
accounting.&#160; All intercompany
transactions and balances between and among Kraft&#146;s subsidiaries have been
eliminated.&#160; Transactions between any of
the Company&#146;s businesses and Altria Group, Inc. and its affiliates are included
in these financial statements.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The
preparation of financial statements in conformity with accounting principles
generally accepted in the United States of America requires management to make
estimates and assumptions that affect the reported amounts of assets and
liabilities, the disclosure of contingent liabilities at the dates of the
financial statements and the reported amounts of net revenues and expenses
during the reporting periods.&#160;
Significant estimates and assumptions include, among other things,
pension and benefit plan assumptions, lives and valuation assumptions of
goodwill and other intangible assets, and income taxes.&#160; Actual results could differ from those
estimates.&#160; The Company&#146;s operating
subsidiaries report year-end results as of the Saturday closest to the end of
each year.</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">6</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='6',FILE='C:\JMS\dholbrook\05-2188-6\task287399\2188-6-mm-01.htm',USER='dholbro',CD='Jan 31 05:17 2005' -->


<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Certain prior
years&#146; amounts have been reclassified to conform with the current year&#146;s
presentation, due primarily to the new segment structure and the classification
of the sugar confectionery business as discontinued operations.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><u><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Note 2.&#160;
Summary of Significant Accounting Policies:</font></u></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:9.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Cash and cash
equivalents:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Cash
equivalents include demand deposits with banks and all highly liquid
investments with original maturities of three months or less.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:9.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Depreciation,
amortization and goodwill valuation:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Property,
plant and equipment are stated at historical cost and depreciated by the
straight-line method over the estimated useful lives of the assets.&#160; Machinery and equipment are depreciated over
periods ranging from 3 to 20 years, and buildings and building improvements
over periods up to 40 years.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Definite life intangible
assets are amortized over their estimated useful lives.&#160; The Company is required to conduct an annual
review of goodwill and intangible assets for potential impairment.&#160; Goodwill impairment testing requires a
comparison between the carrying value and fair value of each reporting
unit.&#160; If the carrying value exceeds the
fair value, goodwill is considered impaired.&#160;
The amount of impairment loss is measured as the difference between the
carrying value and implied fair value of goodwill, which is determined using
discounted cash flows.&#160; Impairment
testing for non-amortizable intangible assets requires a comparison between
fair value and carrying value of the intangible asset.&#160; If the carrying value exceeds fair value, the
intangible asset is considered impaired and is reduced to fair value. During
2004, the Company completed its annual review of goodwill and intangible
assets.&#160; This review resulted in a $29
million non-cash pre-tax charge related to an intangible asset impairment for a
small confectionery business in the United States and certain brands in
Mexico.&#160; A portion of this charge, $12
million, was recorded as asset impairment and exit costs on the consolidated
statement of earnings.&#160; The remainder of
the charge, $17 million, is included in discontinued operations.</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">At December&nbsp;31, 2004 and 2003, goodwill
by reportable segment was as follows (in millions):</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:1.0in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="80%" style="border-collapse:collapse;margin-left:.35in;width:80.0%;">
 <tr>
  <td width="61%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:61.06%;">
  <p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><b><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;font-weight:bold;">&nbsp;</font></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:2.44%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;font-weight:bold;">&nbsp;</font></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width="16%" colspan="2" valign="bottom" style="border:none;border-bottom:solid windowtext 1.0pt;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:16.52%;">
  <p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><b><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:8.0pt;font-weight:bold;">2004</font></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:2.44%;">
  <p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><b><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;font-weight:bold;">&nbsp;</font></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width="16%" colspan="2" valign="bottom" style="border:none;border-bottom:solid windowtext 1.0pt;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:16.54%;">
  <p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><b><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:8.0pt;font-weight:bold;">2003</font></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width="1%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:1.0%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;font-weight:bold;">&nbsp;</font></b></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
 <tr>
  <td width="61%" valign="top" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:61.06%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 10.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:2.44%;">

  </td>
  <td width="16%" colspan="2" valign="bottom" style="border:none;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:16.52%;">

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Non-amortizable intangible
assets are substantially comprised of brand names purchased through the Nabisco
acquisition.&#160; Amortizable intangible
assets consist primarily of certain trademark licenses and non-compete agreements.&#160; Pre-tax amortization expense for intangible
assets was $11 million, $9 million and $7 million for the years ended December&nbsp;31,
2004, 2003 and 2002, respectively.&#160;
Amortization expense for each of the next five years is currently
estimated to be $12 million or less.</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The movement in goodwill and
gross carrying amount of intangible assets is as follows:</font></p>

  </td>
  <td width="1%" valign="bottom" style="border:none;border-bottom:double windowtext 1.5pt;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:1.3%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">$</font></p>
  </td>

  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">10,685</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:2.0%;">

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Other, above,
includes the reclassification to goodwill of certain amounts previously
classified as indefinite life intangible assets, as well as tax adjustments
related to the Nabisco acquisition.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:9.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Environmental
costs:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company is
subject to laws and regulations relating to the protection of the
environment.&#160; The Company provides for
expenses associated with environmental remediation obligations on an
undiscounted basis when such amounts are probable and can be reasonably
estimated.&#160; Such accruals are adjusted as
new information develops or circumstances change.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">While it is
not possible to quantify with certainty the potential impact of actions
regarding environmental remediation and compliance efforts that the Company may
undertake in the future, in the opinion of management, environmental
remediation and compliance costs, before taking into account any recoveries</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">8</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='8',FILE='C:\JMS\dholbrook\05-2188-6\task287399\2188-6-mm-01.htm',USER='dholbro',CD='Jan 31 05:17 2005' -->


<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">from third
parties, will not have a material adverse effect on the Company&#146;s consolidated
financial position, results of operations or cash flows.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:9.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Foreign
currency translation:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company
translates the results of operations of its foreign subsidiaries using average
exchange rates during each period, whereas balance sheet accounts are
translated using exchange rates at the end of each period.&#160; Currency translation adjustments are recorded
as a component of shareholders&#146; equity.&#160;
Transaction gains and losses are recorded in the consolidated statements
of earnings and were not significant for any of the periods presented.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:9.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Guarantees:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Effective January&nbsp;1,
2003, the Company adopted Financial Accounting Standards Board (&#147;FASB&#148;)
Interpretation No. 45, &#147;Guarantor&#146;s Accounting and Disclosure Requirements for
Guarantees, Including Indirect Guarantees of Indebtedness of Others.&#148;&#160; Interpretation No. 45 required the disclosure
of certain guarantees existing at December&nbsp;31, 2002.&#160; In addition, Interpretation No. 45 requires
the recognition of a liability for the fair value of the obligation of
qualifying guarantee activities initiated or modified after December&nbsp;31,
2002.&#160; The Company has applied the
recognition provisions of Interpretation No. 45 to guarantee activity initiated
after December&nbsp;31, 2002.&#160; Adoption
of Interpretation No. 45 as of January&nbsp;1, 2003 did not have a material
impact on the Company&#146;s consolidated financial statements.&#160; See Note 18.&#160;
<i><font style="font-style:italic;">Contingencies</font></i> for a
further discussion of guarantees.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 9.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Hedging
instruments:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Derivative
financial instruments are recorded at fair value on the consolidated balance
sheets as either assets or liabilities.&#160;
Changes in the fair value of derivatives are recorded each period either
in accumulated other comprehensive earnings (losses) or in earnings, depending
on whether a derivative is designated and effective as part of a hedge
transaction and, if it is, the type of hedge transaction.&#160; Gains and losses on derivative instruments
reported in accumulated other comprehensive earnings (losses) are reclassified
to the consolidated statement of earnings in the periods in which operating
results are affected by the hedged item.&#160;
Cash flows from hedging instruments are classified in the same manner as
the affected hedged item in the consolidated statements of cash flows.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:9.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Impairment of
long-lived assets:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company
reviews long-lived assets, including amortizable intangible assets, for
impairment whenever events or changes in business circumstances indicate that
the carrying amount of the assets may not be fully recoverable.&#160; The Company performs undiscounted operating
cash flow analyses to determine if an impairment exists.&#160; For purposes of recognition and measurement
of an impairment for assets held for use, the Company groups assets and
liabilities at the lowest level for which cash flows are separately
identifiable.&#160; If an impairment is
determined to exist, any related impairment loss is calculated based on fair
value.&#160; Impairment losses on assets to be
disposed of, if any, are based on the estimated proceeds to be received, less
costs of disposal.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:9.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Income taxes:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company
accounts for income taxes in accordance with Statement of Financial Accounting
Standards (&#147;SFAS&#148;) No. 109, &#147;Accounting for Income Taxes.&#148; The accounts of the
Company are included in the consolidated federal income tax return of Altria
Group, Inc.&#160; Income taxes are generally
computed on a separate company basis.&#160; To
the extent that foreign tax credits, capital losses and other credits generated
by the Company, which cannot currently be utilized on a separate company basis,
are utilized in Altria Group, Inc.&#146;s consolidated federal income tax return,
the benefit is recognized in the calculation of the Company&#146;s provision for
income taxes.&#160; Based on the Company&#146;s
current estimate, this benefit is calculated to be approximately $70 million,
$100 million and $240 million for the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2004, 2003</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">9</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='9',FILE='C:\JMS\dholbrook\05-2188-6\task287399\2188-6-mm-01.htm',USER='dholbro',CD='Jan 31 05:17 2005' -->


<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div style="font-family:Times New Roman;">

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">and 2002,
respectively.&#160; The Company makes payments
to, or is reimbursed by, Altria Group, Inc. for the tax effects resulting from
its inclusion in Altria Group, Inc.&#146;s consolidated federal income tax
return.&#160; Significant judgment is required
in determining income tax provisions and in evaluating tax positions.&#160; The Company establishes additional provisions
for income taxes when, despite the belief that their tax positions are fully
supportable, there remain certain positions that are likely to be challenged
and that may not be sustained on review by tax authorities.&#160; The Company adjusts these additional accruals
in light of changing facts and circumstances.&#160;
The consolidated tax provision includes the impact of changes to
accruals that are considered appropriate, as well as the related net interest.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:9.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Inventories:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Inventories
are stated at the lower of cost or market.&#160;
The last-in, first-out (&#147;LIFO&#148;) method is used to cost a majority of
domestic inventories.&#160; The cost of other
inventories is principally determined by the average cost method.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In 2004, the
FASB issued SFAS No. 151, &#147;Inventory Costs.&#148;&#160;
SFAS No. 151 requires that abnormal idle facility expense, spoilage,
freight and handling costs be recognized as current-period charges.&#160; In addition, SFAS No. 151 requires that
allocation of fixed production overhead costs to inventories be based on the
normal capacity of the production facility.&#160;
The Company is required to adopt the provisions of SFAS No. 151
prospectively after January&nbsp;1, 2006, but the effect of adoption is not
expected to have a material impact on its consolidated results of operations,
financial position or cash flows.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:9.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Marketing
costs:</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-autospace:none;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company promotes its products with
advertising, consumer incentives and trade promotions.&#160; Such programs include, but are not limited
to, discounts, coupons, rebates, in-store display incentives and volume- based
incentives.&#160; Advertising costs are
expensed as incurred.&#160; </font>Consumer incentive and trade promotion
activities are recorded as a reduction of revenues based on amounts estimated
as being due to customers and consumers at the end of a period, based
principally on historical utilization and redemption rates.&#160; For interim reporting purposes, advertising
and consumer incentive expenses are charged to operations as a percentage of
volume, based on estimated volume and related expense for the full year.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-autospace:none;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:9.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Revenue
recognition:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company
recognizes revenues, net of sales incentives and including shipping and
handling charges billed to customers, upon shipment of goods when title and
risk of loss pass to customers.&#160; Shipping
and handling costs are classified as part of cost of sales.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:9.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Software
costs:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company
capitalizes certain computer software and software development costs incurred
in connection with developing or obtaining computer software for internal
use.&#160; Capitalized software costs are included
in property, plant and equipment on the consolidated balance sheets and
amortized on a straight-line basis over the estimated useful lives of the
software, which do not exceed five years.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:9.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Stock-based
compensation:</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The
Company accounts for employee stock compensation plans in accordance with the
intrinsic value-based method permitted by SFAS No. 123, &#147;Accounting for
Stock-Based Compensation,&#148; which has not resulted in compensation cost for
stock options.&#160; The market value at date
of grant of restricted stock and rights to receive shares of stock is recorded
as compensation expense over the period of restriction.</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">At December&nbsp;31, 2004, the Company had
stock-based employee compensation plans, which are described more fully in Note
11. <i><font style="font-style:italic;">Stock Plans.&#160; </font></i>The Company applies the
recognition and measurement principles of Accounting Principles Board Opinion
No. 25, &#147;Accounting for Stock Issued to Employees,&#148; and related</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">10</font></p>

<div align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:11.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

in accounting for stock options within those plans.&#160; No compensation expense for employee stock
options is reflected in net earnings, as all stock options granted under those
plans had an exercise price equal to the market value of the common stock on
the date of grant.&#160; Net earnings, as
reported, includes pre-tax compensation expense related to restricted stock and

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 9.0pt;text-align:left;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;">In 2004, the FASB issued
SFAS No. 123 (revised 2004), &#147;Share-Based Payment&#148; (&#147;SFAS No. 123R&#148;).&#160; SFAS No. 123R requires companies to measure compensation
cost for share-based payments at fair value.&#160;
The Company will adopt this new standard prospectively on July&nbsp;1,
2005, and does not expect the adoption of SFAS No. 123R to have a material
impact on its 2005 consolidated </font>financial position, results of
operations or cash flows.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><u><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Note 3.&#160;
Asset Impairment, Exit and Implementation Costs:</font></u></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Restructuring Program:</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In January&nbsp;2004,
the Company announced a three-year restructuring program with the objectives of
leveraging the Company&#146;s global scale, realigning and lowering its cost
structure, and optimizing capacity utilization.&#160;
As part of this program, the Company anticipates the closing or sale of
up to twenty plants and the elimination of approximately six thousand
positions.&#160; From 2004 through 2006, the
Company expects to incur up to $1.2 billion in pre-tax charges, reflecting
asset disposals, severance and other implementation costs, including $641
million incurred in 2004.&#160; Approximately
one-half of the pre-tax charges are expected to require cash payments.</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">11</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>

<div>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Restructuring Costs:</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">During 2004,
pre-tax charges under the restructuring program of $583 million were recorded
as asset impairment and exit costs on the consolidated statement of
earnings.&#160; These charges resulted from
the 2004 announcement of the closing of thirteen plants, the termination of
co-manufacturing agreements and the commencement of a number of workforce
reduction programs.&#160; Approximately $216
million of the pre-tax charges incurred in 2004 will require cash payments.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

as follows:</font></p>

  <td width="12%" colspan="2" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:12.0%;">

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:9.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Severance
costs in the above schedule, which relate to the workforce reduction programs,
include the cost of related benefits.&#160;
Specific programs announced during 2004, as part of the overall
restructuring program, will result in the elimination of approximately 3,500
positions.&#160; Asset write-downs relate to
the impairment of assets caused by the plant closings.&#160; Other costs incurred relate primarily to
contract termination costs associated with the plant closings and the
termination of co-manufacturing agreements.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Implementation Costs:</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">During 2004,
the Company recorded $58 million of pre-tax implementation costs associated
with the restructuring program, of which $7 million was recorded as a reduction
of net revenues, $30 million was recorded in cost of sales, $13 million was
recorded in marketing, administration and research costs, and $8 million
related to the sugar confectionery business was recorded in loss from
discontinued operations, on the consolidated statement of earnings.&#160; These costs include the discontinuance of
certain product lines and incremental costs related to the integration of
functions and closure of facilities.&#160;
Approximately $36 million of these costs will require cash payments.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.5in;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Asset Impairment Charges:</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">During 2004,
the Company completed its annual review of goodwill and intangible assets.&#160; This review resulted in a $29 million
non-cash pre-tax charge related to an intangible asset impairment for a small
confectionery business in the United States and certain brands in Mexico.&#160; A portion of this charge, $17 million,
relates to the sugar confectionery business and has been recorded in loss from
discontinued operations on the consolidated statement of earnings.&#160; The remaining charge was recorded as asset
impairment and exit costs on the consolidated statement of earnings.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In November&nbsp;2004,
the Company completed a valuation of its equity investment in a joint venture
in Turkey following the determination that a non-temporary decline in value had
occurred.&#160; This valuation resulted in a
$47 million non-cash pre-tax charge.&#160;
This charge was recorded as marketing, administration and research costs
on the consolidated statement of earnings.</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">12</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">On November&nbsp;15,
2004, the Company announced the sale of substantially all of its sugar confectionery
business for approximately $1.5 billion.&#160;
As a result of the anticipated transaction, which is expected to close
in the second quarter of 2005, the Company recorded non-cash asset impairments
totaling $107 million.&#160; This charge was
included in loss from discontinued operations on the consolidated statement of
earnings.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In December&nbsp;2004,
the Company announced the sale of its yogurt business for approximately $59
million.&#160; As a result of the anticipated
transaction, which is expected to close in the first quarter of 2005, the
Company recorded asset impairments totaling $8 million.&#160; This charge was recorded as asset impairment
and exit costs on the consolidated statement of earnings.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.5in;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Total:</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The pre-tax
asset impairment, exit and implementation costs discussed above, for the year
ended December&nbsp;31, 2004, were included in the operating companies income
of the following segments:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Other:</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">During 2003, the Company
recorded a pre-tax charge of $6 million for asset impairment and exit costs
related to the closure of a Nordic snacks plant.&#160; During 2002, the Company recorded a pre-tax charge
of $142 million related to employee acceptances under a voluntary retirement
program.&#160; Approximately 700 employees
elected to retire or terminate employment under the program.&#160; These charges were included in the operating
companies income of the following segments for the years ended December&nbsp;31,
2003 and 2002:</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><u><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Note 4.&#160; Related Party
Transactions:</font></u></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Altria Group,
Inc.&#146;s subsidiary, Altria Corporate Services, Inc., provides the Company with
various services, including planning, legal, treasury, accounting, auditing,
insurance, human resources, office of the secretary, corporate affairs,
information technology, aviation and tax services.&#160; Billings for these services, which were based
on the cost to Altria Corporate Services, Inc. to provide such services and a
management fee, were $310 million, $318 million and $327 million for the years
ended December 31, 2004, 2003 and 2002, respectively.&#160; These costs were paid to Altria Corporate
Services, Inc. monthly.&#160; Although the
cost of these services cannot be quantified on a stand-alone basis, management
has assessed that the billings are reasonable based on the level of support
provided by Altria Corporate Services, Inc., and that they reflect all services
provided.&#160; The cost and nature of the
services are reviewed annually by the Company&#146;s Audit Committee, which is
comprised of independent directors.&#160; The
effects of these transactions are included in operating cash flows in the
Company&#146;s consolidated statements of cash flows.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In December 2004,
the Company purchased two corporate aircraft from Altria Corporate Services,
Inc. for an aggregate purchase price of approximately $47 million.&#160; The Company also entered into an Aircraft
Management Agreement with Altria Corporate Services, Inc. in December 2004,
pursuant to which Altria Corporate Services, Inc. agreed to perform aircraft
management, pilot services, maintenance and other aviation services for the
Company.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">During 2004,
Altria Corporate Services, Inc. provided to the Company certain financial
services, including payroll and accounts payable processing, at a cost of
approximately $25 million, which was included in the $310 million charge shown
above.&#160; Beginning in 2005, the Company
will perform these functions for itself at a similar cost.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">At December
31, 2004 and 2003, the Company had short-term amounts payable to Altria Group,
Inc. of $227 million and $543 million, respectively.&#160;&#160; Interest on these borrowings is based on the
applicable London Interbank Offered Rate.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The fair
values of the Company&#146;s short-term amounts due to Altria Group, Inc. and
affiliates approximate carrying amounts.</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">14</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><u><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Note 5.&#160; Divestitures:</font></u></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Discontinued Operations:</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">On November
15, 2004, the Company announced the sale of substantially all of its sugar
confectionery business for approximately $1.5 billion.&#160; The proposed sale includes the <i><font style="font-style:italic;">Life Savers</font></i>, <i><font style="font-style:italic;">Creme Savers</font></i>, <i><font style="font-style:italic;">Altoids</font></i>, <i><font style="font-style:italic;">Trolli</font></i> and <i><font style="font-style:italic;">Sugus</font></i> brands. The transaction, which is subject to
regulatory approval, is expected to be completed in the second quarter of
2005.&#160; The Company has reflected the
results of its sugar confectionery business as discontinued operations on the
consolidated statements of earnings for all years presented.&#160; Pursuant to the sugar confectionery sale
agreement, the Company has agreed to provide certain transition and supply
services to the buyer.&#160; These service
arrangements are primarily for terms of one year or less, with the exception of
one supply arrangement with a term of not more than three years.&#160; The expected cash flow from this supply
arrangement is not significant.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Summary
results of operations for the sugar confectionery business were as follows:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="85%" style="border-collapse:collapse;margin-left:.75in;width:85.0%;">
 <tr>
  <td width="57%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:57.0%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;font-weight:bold;">&nbsp;</font></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:2.0%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;font-weight:bold;">&nbsp;</font></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width="40%" colspan="8" valign="bottom" style="border:none;border-bottom:solid windowtext 1.0pt;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:40.34%;">
  <p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><b><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:8.0pt;font-weight:bold;">For the Years Ended December 31,</font></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width="0%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:.66%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;font-weight:bold;">&nbsp;</font></b></p>
  </td>
 </tr>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In addition,
the Company expects additional tax expense of approximately $270 million to be
recorded as a loss on sale of discontinued operations in 2005.&#160; In accordance with the provisions of SFAS No.
109, the tax expense will be recorded when the transaction is consummated.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

discontinued operations held for sale on the consolidated balance sheet at

the Company sold a Brazilian snack nuts business and trademarks associated with
a candy business in Norway.&#160; The
aggregate proceeds received from the sale of these businesses were $18 million,
on which</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">pre-tax losses of $3 million were
recorded.&#160; In December 2004, the Company
announced the sale of its U.K. desserts business for approximately $135
million, which is expected to result in an estimated gain of $0.04 per
share.&#160; The transaction, which is subject
to required approvals, is expected to close in the first quarter of 2005,
following completion of necessary employee consultation requirements.&#160; The Company also announced in December 2004,
the sale of its yogurt business for approximately $59 million, which is
expected to result in an after-tax loss of approximately $12 million ($5
million in 2004, with the remainder at closing).&#160; The transaction, which is also subject to
regulatory approval, is expected to be completed in the first quarter of 2005.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">During 2003, the Company
sold a European rice business and a branded fresh cheese business in Italy. The
aggregate proceeds received from sales of businesses were $96 million, on which
the Company recorded pre-tax gains of $31 million.</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">During 2002, the Company
sold several small North American food businesses, some of which had been
previously classified as businesses held for sale arising from the acquisition
of Nabisco.&#160; The net revenues and operating
results of the businesses held for sale, which were not significant, were
excluded from the Company&#146;s consolidated statements of earnings, and no gain or
loss was recognized on these sales.&#160; In
addition, the Company sold its Latin American yeast and industrial bakery
ingredients business for approximately $110 million and recorded a pre-tax gain
of $69 million.&#160; The aggregate proceeds
received from sales of businesses were $219 million, on which the Company
recorded pre-tax gains of $80 million.</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The operating
results of the other businesses sold, discussed above, were not material to the
Company&#146;s consolidated financial position, results of operations or cash flows
in any of the periods presented.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><u><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Note 6.&#160; Acquisitions:</font></u></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">During 2004, the Company
acquired a U.S.-based beverage business for a total cost of $137 million.</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">During 2003, the Company
acquired a biscuits business in Egypt and trademarks associated with a small
U.S.-based natural foods business.&#160; The
total cost of these and other smaller acquisitions was $98 million.</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">During 2002,
the Company acquired a snacks business in Turkey and a biscuits business in
Australia.&#160; The total cost of these and
other smaller acquisitions was $122 million.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The effects of
these acquisitions were not material to the Company&#146;s consolidated financial
position, results of operations or cash flows in any of the periods presented.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><u><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Note 7.&#160; Inventories: </font></u></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The cost of
approximately 37% and 39% of inventories in 2004 and 2003, respectively, was
determined using the LIFO method.&#160; The
stated LIFO amounts of inventories were approximately $81 million and $155
million higher than the current cost of inventories at December 31, 2004 and
2003, respectively.</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">16</font></p>

<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><u><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Note 8.&#160; Short-Term Borrowings
and Borrowing Arrangements:</font></u></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">At December
31, 2004 and 2003, the Company had short-term borrowings of $1,818 million and
$2,453 million, respectively, consisting principally of commercial paper
borrowings with an average year-end interest rate of 2.4% and 1.4%,
respectively.&#160; Of these amounts, the
Company reclassified $1,900 million at December 31, 2003, of the commercial
paper borrowings to long-term debt based upon its intent and ability to
refinance these borrowings on a long-term basis.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The fair
values of the Company&#146;s short-term borrowings at December 31, 2004 and 2003,
based upon current market interest rates, approximate the amounts disclosed
above.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Following a $10.1 billion
judgment on March 21, 2003, against Altria Group, Inc.&#146;s domestic tobacco
subsidiary, Philip Morris USA Inc., the three major credit rating agencies took
a series of ratings actions resulting in the lowering of the Company&#146;s
short-term and long-term debt ratings, despite the fact the Company is neither
a party to, nor has exposure to, this litigation.&#160; The Company&#146;s credit ratings by Moody&#146;s at
December 31, 2004, were &#147;P-2&#148; for short-term debt and &#147;A3&#148; for long-term-debt,
with stable outlook.&#160; The Company&#146;s
credit ratings by Standard &amp; Poor&#146;s at December 31, 2004 were &#147;A-2&#148; for
short-term debt and &#147;BBB+&#148; for long-term debt, with stable outlook.&#160; The Company&#146;s credit ratings by Fitch Rating
Services at December 31, 2004 were &#147;F-2&#148; for short-term debt and &#147;BBB+&#148; for
long-term debt, with stable outlook.&#160;
None of the Company&#146;s debt agreements requires accelerated repayment in
the event of a decrease in credit ratings.</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company maintains
revolving credit facilities that have historically been used to support the
issuance of commercial paper.&#160; The
364-day revolving credit facility expires in July 2005, although it contains a
provision allowing the Company to extend the maturity of outstanding borrowings
for up to one additional year.&#160; At
December 31, 2004, credit lines for the Company and the related activity were
as follows (in billions of dollars):</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company&#146;s revolving
credit facilities, which are for its sole use, require the maintenance of a
minimum net worth of $18.2 billion.&#160; At
December 31, 2004, the Company&#146;s net worth was $29.9 billion.&#160; The Company expects to continue to meet this
covenant.&#160; The foregoing revolving credit
facilities do not include any other financial tests, any credit rating triggers
or any provisions that could require the posting of collateral.</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In addition to the above,
certain international subsidiaries of Kraft maintain uncommitted credit lines
to meet the short-term working capital needs of the international
businesses.&#160; These credit lines, which
amounted to approximately $600 million as of December 31, 2004, are for the
sole use of the Company&#146;s international businesses.&#160; Borrowings on these lines amounted to
approximately $150 million and $220 million at December 31, 2004 and 2003,
respectively. </font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">17</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

market quotes, where available, or interest rates currently available to the
Company for issuance of debt with similar terms and remaining maturities, the
aggregate fair value of the Company&#146;s long-term debt, including the current
portion of long-term debt, was $11,017 million and $12,873 million at December
31, 2004 and 2003, respectively.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Kraft
repurchases its Class A common stock in open market transactions.&#160; On December 14, 2004, Kraft completed a
multi-year $700 million Class A common stock repurchase program, acquiring
21,718,847 Class A shares at an average price of $32.23 per share.&#160; During 2004, repurchases under the $700
million program were 20,135,247 shares at a cost of $650 million, or $32.28 per
share.&#160; On December 14, 2004, the Company
commenced repurchasing shares under a new $1.5 billion Class A common stock
repurchase program that was authorized by the Board of Directors on December 2,
2004.&#160; Through December 31, 2004,
repurchases under the $1.5 billion program were 1,408,413 shares at a cost of
$50 million, or $35.49 per share.&#160; On
December 3, 2003, Kraft completed a $500 million Class A common stock
repurchase program, acquiring 15,308,458 Class A shares at an average price of
$32.66 per share.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In addition,
1.18 billion Class B common shares were issued and outstanding at December 31,
2004 and 2003.&#160; Altria Group, Inc. holds
276.5 million Class A common shares and all of the Class B common shares at
December 31, 2004.&#160; There are no
preferred shares issued and outstanding.&#160;
Class A common shares are entitled to one vote each, while Class B
common shares are entitled to ten votes each.&#160;
Therefore, Altria Group, Inc. holds 98.0% of the combined voting power
of the Company&#146;s outstanding capital stock at December 31, 2004.&#160; At December 31, 2004, 66,663,515 shares of
common stock were reserved for stock options and other stock awards.</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">19</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><u><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Note 11.&#160; Stock Plans:</font></u></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Under the 2001
Kraft Performance Incentive Plan (the &#147;2001 Plan&#148;), the Company may grant stock
options, stock appreciation rights, restricted stock, reload options and other
awards based on the Company&#146;s Class A common stock, as well as
performance-based annual and long-term incentive awards.&#160; A maximum of 75 million shares of the Company&#146;s
Class A common stock may be issued under the 2001 Plan.&#160; In addition, the Company may grant up to
500,000 shares of Class A common stock to members of the Board of Directors who
are not full-time employees of the Company or Altria Group, Inc., or their subsidiaries,
under the Kraft Directors Plan (the &#147;2001 Directors Plan&#148;).&#160; Shares available to be granted under the 2001
Plan and the 2001 Directors Plan at December 31, 2004, were 46,707,241 and
458,633, respectively.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company
applies the intrinsic value-based methodology in accounting for the various
stock plans.&#160; Accordingly, no
compensation expense has been recognized other than for restricted stock
awards.&#160; In December 2004, the FASB
issued SFAS No. 123R, which requires companies to measure compensation cost for
share-based payments at fair value.&#160; The
Company will adopt this new standard prospectively on July 1, 2005.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Stock option
activity was as follows for the years ended December 31, 2002, 2003 and 2004:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Prior to the
IPO, certain employees of the Company participated in Altria Group, Inc.&#146;s
stock compensation plans.&#160; Altria Group,
Inc. does not intend to issue additional Altria Group, Inc. stock compensation
to the Company&#146;s employees, except for reloads of previously issued
options.&#160; Altria Group, Inc. accounts for
its plans in accordance with the intrinsic value-based method permitted by SFAS
No. 123, &#147;Accounting for Stock-Based Compensation,&#148; which did not result in
compensation cost for stock options.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company&#146;s
employees held options to purchase the following number of shares of Altria
Group, Inc. stock at December 31, 2004:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">At December
31, 2003 and 2002, the Company&#146;s employees held options to purchase the
following number of shares of Altria Group, Inc. stock: 39,241,651 shares at an
average exercise price of $37.25 per share at December 31, 2003; and 46,615,162
shares at an average exercise price of $35.78 per share at December 31,
2002.&#160; Of these amounts, the following
were exercisable at each date: 39,025,325 at an average exercise price of
$37.19 per share at December 31, 2003; and 46,231,629 at an average exercise
price of $35.69 per share at December 31, 2002.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Had
compensation cost for stock option awards under the Kraft plans and Altria
Group, Inc. plans been determined by using the fair value at the grant date,
the Company&#146;s net earnings and basic and diluted EPS would have been $2,658
million, $1.56 and $1.55, respectively, for the year ended December 31, 2004;
$3,464 million, $2.01 and $2.00, respectively, for the year ended December 31,
2003; and $3,316 million, $1.91 and $1.91, respectively, for the year ended
December 31, 2002.&#160; The foregoing impact
of compensation cost was determined using a modified Black-Scholes methodology
and the following assumptions:</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The
Company may grant shares of restricted stock and rights to receive shares of
stock to eligible employees, giving them in most instances all of the rights of
stockholders, except that they may not sell, assign, pledge or otherwise encumber
such shares and rights.&#160; Such shares and
rights are subject to forfeiture if certain employment conditions are not
met.&#160; During 2004 and 2003, the Company
granted approximately 4.1 million and 3.7 million restricted Class A shares,
respectively, to eligible U.S.-based employees, and during 2004 and 2003, also
issued to eligible non-U.S. employees rights to receive approximately 1.9
million and 1.6 million Class A equivalent shares, respectively.&#160; The market value per restricted share or
right was $32.23 and $36.56 on the dates of the 2004 and 2003 grants,
respectively.&#160; At December 31, 2004,
restrictions on these shares and rights, net of forfeitures, lapse as
follows:&#160; 2005 &#150; 13,719 shares; 2006 &#150;
4,520,120 shares; 2007 &#150; 5,532,500 shares; 2009 &#150; 150,000 shares; and 2012 &#150;
100,000 shares.</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The fair value of the shares of restricted
stock and rights to receive shares of stock at the date of grant is amortized
to expense ratably over the restriction period.&#160;
The Company recorded compensation expense related to the restricted
stock and rights of $106 million and $57 million for the years ended December
31, 2004 and 2003, respectively.&#160; The
unamortized portion, which is reported on the consolidated balance sheets as a
reduction of earnings reinvested in the business, was $190 million and $129
million at December 31, 2004 and 2003, respectively.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

diluted EPS from continuing and discontinued operations were calculated using
the following:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">For the 2003
computation, 18 million Class A common stock options were excluded from the
calculation of weighted average shares for diluted EPS because their effects
were antidilutive.</font></p>
