<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The (loss)
earnings from discontinued operations for the year ended December 31, 2004
included a deferred income tax benefit of $43 million.&#160; The Company also anticipates additional tax
expense of approximately $270 million in 2005, once the sale of its sugar
confectionery business has been consummated.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">At December
31, 2004, applicable United States federal income taxes and foreign withholding
taxes have not been provided on approximately $3.8 billion of accumulated
earnings of foreign subsidiaries that are expected to be permanently
reinvested.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">On October 22, 2004, the
American Jobs Creation Act (&#147;the Jobs Act&#148;) was signed into law.&#160; The Jobs Act includes a deduction for 85% of
certain foreign earnings that are repatriated.&#160;
The Company may elect to apply this provision to qualifying earnings
repatriations in 2005 and is conducting analyses of its effects. The U.S.
Treasury Department recently provided additional clarifying language on key
elements of the provision, which is under consideration as part of the Company&#146;s
evaluation.&#160; The Company expects to
complete its evaluation of the effects of the repatriation provision within a
reasonable period of time.&#160; The Company
does not expect the repatriation provisions of the Jobs Act to have a
significant impact on its consolidated results of operations or its
consolidated cash flows.</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Jobs Act also provides tax relief to U.S.
domestic manufacturers by providing a tax deduction up to 9% of the lesser of &#147;qualified
production activities income&#148; or taxable income.&#160; In December 2004, the FASB issued FASB Staff
Position 109-1, &#147;Application of FASB Statement No. 109, &#145;Accounting for Income
Taxes,&#146; to the Tax Deduction on Qualified Production Activities Provided by the
American Jobs Creation Act of 2004&#148; (&#147;FSP 109-1&#148;).&#160; FSP 109-1 requires companies to account for
this deduction as a &#147;special deduction&#148; rather</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">23</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">than
a rate reduction, in accordance with SFAS No. 109, and therefore, the Company
will recognize these benefits, which are not expected to be significant, in the
year earned.</font></p>

rate for the following reasons for the years ended December 31, 2004, 2003 and
2002:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .75in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The tax
provision in 2004 includes an $81 million favorable resolution of an
outstanding tax item, the majority of which occurred in the third quarter of
2004, and the reversal of $35 million of tax accruals that are no longer
required due to tax events that occurred during the first quarter of 2004.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

and liabilities consisted of the following at December 31, 2004 and 2003:</font></p>

<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='24',FILE='C:\JMS\ethompsb\05-2188-6\task290176\2188-6-mm-03.htm',USER='ethompsb',CD='Feb  2 13:13 2005' -->


<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div style="font-family:Times New Roman;">

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><u><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Note 14.&#160; Segment Reporting:</font></u></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company manufactures and markets packaged
food products, consisting principally of beverages, cheese, snacks, convenient
meals and various packaged grocery products.&#160;
Kraft manages and reports operating results through two units, Kraft
North America Commercial and Kraft International Commercial.&#160; Reportable segments for Kraft North America
Commercial are organized and managed principally by product category.&#160; Kraft International Commercial&#146;s operations
are organized and managed by geographic location.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;">During January 2004, the Company announced a new
global organizational structure, which resulted in new segments.&#160; During the fourth quarter of 2004, following
the sale of its sugar confectionery business, as discussed in Note 5. <i><font style="font-style:italic;">Divestitures</font></i>, the Company realigned its
North American segments.&#160; </font>Kraft
North America Commercial&#146;s new segments are </font>U.S. Beverages; U.S. Cheese, Canada &amp; North America Foodservice;
U.S. Convenient Meals; U.S. Grocery; and U.S. Snacks &amp; Cereals.&#160; Kraft International Commercial&#146;s segments are
Europe, Middle East &amp; Africa; and Latin America &amp; Asia Pacific.&#160; The
new segment structure in North America reflects a shift of certain divisions
and brands between segments to more closely align these businesses to consumer
sectors, to provide more focus on the separate beverage and grocery businesses,
and to benefit from synergies in grain based products.&#160; Historical data have been restated to reflect
the new segment structure.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company&#146;s
management uses operating companies income, which is defined as operating
income before general corporate expenses and amortization of intangibles, to
evaluate segment performance and allocate resources.&#160; Management believes it is appropriate to
disclose this measure to help investors analyze the business performance and
trends of the various business segments.&#160;
Interest and other debt expense, net, and provision for income taxes are
centrally managed and, accordingly, such items are not presented by segment
since they are not included in the measure of segment profitability reviewed by
management.&#160; The Company&#146;s assets, which
are principally in the United States and Europe, are managed
geographically.&#160; The accounting policies
of the segments are the same as those described in Note 2. <i><font style="font-style:italic;">Summary of
Significant Accounting Policies</font></i>.</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">25</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company&#146;s
largest customer, Wal-Mart Stores, Inc. and its affiliates, accounted for
approximately 14%, 12% and 12% of consolidated net revenues for 2004, 2003 and
2002, respectively.&#160; These net revenues
occurred primarily in the United States and were across all segments.</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">27</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='27',FILE='C:\JMS\ethompsb\05-2188-6\task290176\2188-6-mm-03.htm',USER='ethompsb',CD='Feb  2 13:13 2005' -->


<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div style="font-family:Times New Roman;">

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .25in;text-indent:-9.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Items
affecting the comparability of the Company&#146;s continuing operating results were
as follows:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .25in;text-indent:-9.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt 34.55pt;text-indent:-.35in;"><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;">&#149;</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font><i><font style="font-style:italic;">Asset Impairment, Exit and Implementation Costs &#150;</font></i> As discussed in Note 3. <i><font style="font-style:italic;">Asset Impairment, Exit and Implementation Costs</font></i>,
the Company recorded asset impairment, exit and implementation costs of $700
million, $6 million and $142 million for the years ended December 31, 2004,
2003 and 2002, respectively.&#160; See Note 3
for the breakdown of these pre-tax
charges by segment.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt 34.55pt;text-indent:-.35in;"><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;">&#149;</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font><i><font style="font-style:italic;">Losses (Gains) on Sales of Businesses &#150;</font></i> During 2004, the Company
sold a Brazilian snack nuts business and trademarks associated with a candy
business in Norway for aggregate pre-tax losses of $3 million.&#160; During
2003, the Company sold a European rice business and a branded fresh cheese
business in Italy for aggregate pre-tax gains of $31 million.&#160; During 2002, the <i><font style="font-style:italic;">Company</font></i> sold its Latin American yeast and industrial bakery
ingredients business, resulting in a pre-tax gain of $69 million, and several
small food businesses, resulting in pre-tax gains of $11 million.&#160; These pre-tax losses (gains) were included in
the operating companies income of the following segments:</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 9.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

  <td width="10%" valign="bottom" style="border-bottom:double windowtext 1.5pt;border-left:none;border-right:none;border-top:solid windowtext 1.0pt;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:10.5%;">
  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">(31</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:2.0%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">)</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="1%" valign="bottom" style="border:none;border-bottom:double windowtext 1.5pt;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:1.52%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">$</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="10%" valign="bottom" style="border-bottom:double windowtext 1.5pt;border-left:none;border-right:none;border-top:solid windowtext 1.0pt;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:10.56%;">
  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">(80</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="0%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:.9%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">)</font></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 9.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt 34.55pt;text-indent:-.35in;"><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;">&#149;</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font><i><font style="font-style:italic;">Integration Costs and a Loss on Sale of a Food Factory -</font></i> During 2003, the Company reversed $13 million
related to the previously recorded integration charges.&#160; During 2002, the Company recorded pre-tax
integration-related charges of $115 million to consolidate production lines in
North America, close a Kraft facility and for other consolidation programs.&#160; In addition, during 2002, the Company reversed
$4 million related to the loss on sale of a food factory.&#160; These items were included in the operating <font size="3" style="font-size:12.0pt;">companies</font> income of the following segments:</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><u><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Note
15.&#160; Benefit Plans:</font></u></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In December 2003, the FASB
issued a revised SFAS No. 132, &#147;Employers&#146; Disclosures about Pensions and Other
Postretirement Benefits.&#148;&#160; In accordance
with the pronouncement, the Company adopted the revised disclosure requirements
of this pronouncement for its U.S. plans in 2003 and for its non-U.S. plans in
2004.</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company sponsors
noncontributory defined benefit pension plans covering substantially all U.S.
employees.&#160; Pension coverage for
employees of the Company&#146;s non-U.S. subsidiaries is provided, to the extent
deemed appropriate, through separate plans, many of which are governed by local
statutory requirements.&#160; In addition, the
Company&#146;s U.S. and Canadian subsidiaries provide health care and other benefits
to substantially all retired employees.&#160;
Health care benefits for retirees outside the United States and Canada
are generally covered through local government plans.</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The plan assets and benefit
obligations of the Company&#146;s U.S. and Canadian pension plans are measured at
December 31 of each year and all other non-U.S. pension plans are measured at
September 30 of each year.&#160; The benefit
obligations of the Company&#146;s postretirement plans are measured at December 31
of each year.</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">30</font></p>

<div align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .75in;text-align:left;text-indent:-45.0pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Obligations

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The combined U.S. and
non-U.S. pension plans resulted in a net prepaid pension asset of $2,404
million and $1,985 million at December 31, 2004 and 2003, respectively.&#160; These amounts were recognized in the Company&#146;s
consolidated balance sheets at December 31, 2004 and 2003, as prepaid pension
assets of $3,569 million and $3,243 million, respectively, for those plans in
which plan assets exceeded their accumulated benefit obligations, and as other
liabilities of $1,165 million and $1,258 million, respectively, for plans in
which the accumulated benefit obligations exceeded their plan assets.</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">31</font></p>

<div align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">For U.S. and non-U.S.
pension plans, the change in the additional minimum liability in 2004 and 2003
was as follows:</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The accumulated benefit
obligation for the U.S. pension plans was $5,327 million and $4,898 million at
December 31, 2004 and 2003, respectively.&#160;
The accumulated benefit obligation for the non-U.S. pension plans was
$3,251 million and $2,708 million at December 31, 2004 and 2003, respectively.</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">At December 31, 2004 and
2003, certain of the Company&#146;s U.S. pension plans were underfunded, with
projected benefit obligations, accumulated benefit obligations and the fair
value of plan assets of $260 million, $188 million and $11 million,
respectively, in 2004, and $261 million, $208 million and $14 million,
respectively, in 2003.&#160; The majority of
these relate to plans for salaried employees that cannot be funded under IRS
regulations.&#160; For certain non-U.S. plans,
which have accumulated benefit obligations in excess of plan assets, the
projected benefit obligation, accumulated benefit obligation and fair value of
plan assets were $2,012 million, $1,877 million and $950 million, respectively,
as of December 31, 2004, and $1,648 million, $1,532 million and $588 million,
respectively, as of December 31, 2003.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The following weighted-average
assumptions were used to determine the Company&#146;s benefit obligations under the
plans at December 31:</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">4.00</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:2.34%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="11%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:11.7%;">
  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">3.11</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:2.34%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="11%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:11.7%;">
  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">3.11</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="1%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:1.16%;">

</table>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .75in;text-align:left;text-indent:-45.0pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Components
of Net Periodic Benefit Cost</font></b></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .75in;text-align:left;text-indent:-45.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Net periodic pension cost
(income) consisted of the following for the years ended December 31, 2004, 2003
and 2002:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Retiring employees elected
lump-sum payments, resulting in settlement losses of $41 million, $51 million
and $21 million in 2004, 2003 and 2002, respectively.&#160; In addition, during 2002, certain salaried
employees in the United States left the Company under a voluntary early
retirement program instituted in 2001.&#160;
This resulted in special termination benefits and curtailment and
settlement losses of $109 million in 2002.&#160;
In 2004, a non-U.S. plant closure and early retirement benefits resulted
in curtailment and settlement losses of $7 million.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The following
weighted-average assumptions were used to determine the Company&#146;s net pension
cost for the years ended December 31:</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="8%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:8.48%;">
  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">4.00</font></p>
  </td>

  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">3.36</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="1%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:1.04%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

</table>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company&#146;s expected rate
of return on plan assets is determined by the plan assets&#146; historical long-term
investment performance, current asset allocation and estimates of future
long-term returns by asset class.&#160; The
Company has reduced this assumption to 8% in determining its U.S. plans pension
expense for 2005.&#160; In 2005, the discount
rate used to determine the Company&#146;s net pension cost for its U.S. plans will
be 5.75% and the rate of compensation increase for its U.S. plans will be
4.00%.</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Kraft and certain of its
subsidiaries sponsor employee savings plans, to which the Company contributes.
These plans cover certain salaried, non-union and union employees.&#160; The Company&#146;s contributions and costs are
determined by the matching of employee contributions, as defined by the plans. &#160;Amounts charged to expense for defined
contribution plans totaled $92 million, $84 million and $64 million in 2004,
2003 and 2002, respectively.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .75in;text-align:left;text-indent:-45.0pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Plan Assets</font></b></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The percentage of fair value
of pension plan assets at December 31, 2004 and 2003, was as follows:</font></p>

  <td width="11%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;border:none;border-bottom:double windowtext 1.5pt;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:11.7%;">
  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">100</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in .7pt 0in;width:2.92%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">%</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="11%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;border:none;border-bottom:double windowtext 1.5pt;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:11.96%;">
  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">100</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in .7pt 0in;width:2.92%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">%</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="11%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;border:none;border-bottom:double windowtext 1.5pt;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:11.7%;">
  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">100</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in .7pt 0in;width:2.92%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">%</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="11%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;border:none;border-bottom:double windowtext 1.5pt;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:11.88%;">
  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">100</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="0%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in .7pt 0in;width:.96%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">%</font></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company&#146;s investment
strategy is based on an expectation that equity securities will outperform debt
securities over the long term.&#160;
Accordingly, the composition of the Company&#146;s U.S. plan assets is
broadly characterized as a 70%/30% allocation between equity and debt
securities.&#160; The strategy utilizes
indexed U.S. equity securities and actively managed investment grade debt
securities (which constitute 80% or more of debt securities) with lesser
allocations to high yield and international debt securities.</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">33</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='33',FILE='C:\JMS\smani\05-2188-6\task287381\2188-6-mm-05.htm',USER='smani',CD='Jan 31 15:15 2005' -->


<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">For the plans outside the
U.S., the investment strategy is subject to local regulations and the
asset/liability profiles of the plans in each individual country.&#160; These specific circumstances result in a
level of equity exposure that is typically less than the U.S. plans.&#160; In aggregate, the actual asset allocations of
the non-U.S. plans are virtually identical to their respective asset policy
targets.</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company attempts to
mitigate investment risk by rebalancing between equity and debt asset classes
as the Company&#146;s contributions and monthly benefit payments are made.</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company presently plans
to make contributions, to the extent that they are tax deductible, in order to
maintain plan assets in excess of the accumulated benefit obligation of its
funded U.S. and non-U.S. plans.&#160;
Currently, the Company anticipates making contributions of approximately
$250 million in 2005 to its U.S. plans and approximately $90 million in 2005 to
its non-U.S. plans, based on current tax law.&#160;
However, these estimates are subject to change as a result of changes in
tax law, as well as asset performance significantly above or below the assumed
long-term rate of return on pension assets, or significant changes in interest
rates.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The estimated future benefit
payments from the Company&#146;s pension plans at December 31, 2004, were as
follows:</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Postretirement Benefit Plans</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Net postretirement health
care costs consisted of the following for the years ended December 31, 2004,
2003 and 2002:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

  <p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><b><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:8.0pt;font-weight:bold;">2004</font></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:2.8%;">

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">During 2002, certain
salaried employees in the United States left the Company under a voluntary
early retirement program instituted in 2001.&#160;
This resulted in curtailment losses of $16 million in 2002, which are
included in other expense above.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In December 2003, the United
States enacted into law the Medicare Prescription Drug, Improvement and
Modernization Act of 2003 (the &#147;Act&#148;).&#160;
The Act establishes a prescription drug benefit under Medicare,</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">34</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='34',FILE='C:\JMS\smani\05-2188-6\task287381\2188-6-mm-05.htm',USER='smani',CD='Jan 31 15:15 2005' -->


<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">known
as &#147;Medicare Part D,&#148; and a federal subsidy to sponsors of retiree health care
benefit plans that provide a benefit that is at least actuarially equivalent to
Medicare Part D.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In May 2004, the FASB issued
FASB Staff Position No. 106-2, &#147;Accounting and Disclosure Requirements Related
to the Medicare Prescription Drug, Improvement and Modernization Act of 2003&#148; (&#147;FSP
106-2&#148;).&#160; FSP 106-2 requires companies to
account for the effect of the subsidy on benefits attributable to past service
as an actuarial experience gain and as a reduction of the service cost
component of net postretirement health care costs for amounts attributable to
current service, if the benefit provided is at least actuarially equivalent to
Medicare Part D.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company adopted FSP
106-2 in the third quarter of 2004.&#160; The
impact of adoption for 2004 was a reduction of pre-tax net postretirement
health care costs and an increase in net earnings of $24 million, which is
included above as a reduction of $3 million in service cost, $10 million in
interest cost and $11 million in amortization of unrecognized net loss from
experience differences.&#160; In addition, as
of July 1, 2004, the Company reduced its accumulated postretirement benefit
obligation for the subsidy related to benefits attributed to past service by
$315 million and decreased its unrecognized actuarial losses by the same
amount.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The following
weighted-average assumptions were used to determine the Company&#146;s net
postretirement cost for the years ended December 31:</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In 2005, the discount rate
used to determine the Company&#146;s net postretirement cost will be 5.75% and the
health care cost trend rate will be 8.00% for its U.S. plans and 9.50% for its
Canadian plans.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company&#146;s postretirement
health care plans are not funded.&#160; The
changes in the accumulated benefit obligation and net amount accrued at
December 31, 2004 and 2003, were as follows:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The current portion of the
Company&#146;s accrued postretirement health care costs of $217 million and $199
million at December 31, 2004 and 2003, respectively, are included in other
accrued liabilities on the consolidated balance sheets.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

weighted-average assumptions were used to determine the Company&#146;s
postretirement benefit obligations at December 31:</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Assumed health care cost
trend rates have a significant effect on the amounts reported for the health
care plans.&#160; A one-percentage-point
change in assumed health care cost trend rates would have the following effects
as of December 31, 2004:</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Postemployment Benefit Plans</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Kraft and certain of its affiliates
sponsor postemployment benefit plans covering substantially all salaried and
certain hourly employees.&#160; The cost of
these plans is charged to expense over the working life of the covered
employees.&#160; Net postemployment costs
consisted of the following for the years ended December 31, 2004, 2003 and
2002:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .75in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">As previously discussed in
Note 3. <i><font style="font-style:italic;">Asset Impairment, Exit and Implementation Costs</font></i>,
the Company announced several workforce reduction programs during 2004 as part
of the overall restructuring program.&#160;
The cost of these programs, $167 million, is included in other expense
above.&#160; During 2002, certain salaried
employees in the United States left the Company under voluntary early
retirement and integration programs.&#160;
These programs resulted in incremental postemployment costs of $23
million, which are included in other expense above.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company&#146;s postemployment
plans are not funded.&#160; The changes in the
benefit obligations of the plans at December 31, 2004 and 2003, were as
follows:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The accumulated benefit
obligation was determined using an assumed ultimate annual turnover rate of
0.3% in 2004 and 2003, assumed compensation cost increases of 4.0% in 2004 and
2003, and assumed benefits as defined in the respective plans.&#160; Postemployment costs arising from actions
that offer employees benefits in excess of those specified in the respective
plans are charged to expense when incurred.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><u><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Note
17. Financial Instruments:</font></u></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.5in;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Derivative
financial instruments</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company operates
globally, with manufacturing and sales facilities in various locations around
the world, and utilizes certain financial instruments to manage its foreign
currency and commodity exposures.&#160;
Derivative financial instruments are used by the Company, principally to
reduce exposures to market risks resulting from fluctuations in foreign
exchange rates and commodity prices by creating offsetting exposures.&#160; The Company is not a party to leveraged
derivatives and, by policy, does not use financial instruments for speculative
purposes.&#160; Financial instruments
qualifying for hedge accounting must maintain a specified level of
effectiveness between the hedging instrument and the item being hedged, both at
inception and throughout the hedged period.&#160;
The Company formally documents the nature of and relationships between
the hedging instruments and hedged items, as well as its risk-management
objectives, strategies for undertaking the various hedge transactions and
method of assessing hedge effectiveness.&#160;
Additionally, for hedges of forecasted transactions, the significant
characteristics and expected terms of the forecasted transaction must be
specifically identified, and it must be probable that each forecasted
transaction will occur.&#160; If it were
deemed probable that the forecasted transaction will not occur, the gain or
loss would be recognized in earnings currently.</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">38</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

<div>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company uses forward
foreign exchange contracts and foreign currency options to mitigate its
exposure to changes in exchange rates from third-party and intercompany actual
and forecasted transactions.&#160;
Substantially all of the Company&#146;s derivative financial instruments are
effective as hedges.&#160; The primary
currencies to which the Company is exposed, based on the size and location of
its businesses, include the euro, Swiss franc, British pound and Canadian
dollar.&#160; At December 31, 2004 and 2003,
the Company had foreign exchange option and forward contracts with aggregate
notional amounts of $2.9 billion and $2.5 billion, respectively.&#160; The effective portion of unrealized gains and
losses associated with forward and option contracts is deferred as a component
of accumulated other comprehensive earnings (losses) until the underlying
hedged transactions are reported on the Company&#146;s consolidated statement of
earnings.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company is exposed to
price risk related to forecasted purchases of certain commodities used as raw
materials by its businesses.&#160;
Accordingly, the Company uses commodity forward contracts as cash flow
hedges, primarily for coffee, cocoa, milk and cheese.&#160; Commodity futures and options are also used
to hedge the price of certain commodities, including milk, coffee, cocoa,
wheat, corn, sugar and soybean oil.&#160; In
general, commodity forward contracts qualify for the normal purchase exception
under SFAS No. 133 and are, therefore, not subject to the provisions of SFAS
No. 133.&#160; At December 31, 2004 and 2003,
the Company had net long commodity positions of $443 million and $255 million,
respectively.&#160; Unrealized gains or losses
on net commodity positions were immaterial at December 31, 2004 and 2003.&#160; The effective portion of unrealized gains and
losses on commodity futures and option contracts is deferred as a component of
accumulated other comprehensive earnings (losses) and is recognized as a
component of cost of sales in the Company&#146;s consolidated statement of earnings
when the related inventory is sold.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Ineffectiveness related to
cash flow hedges was not material for the years ended December 31, 2004, 2003
and 2002.&#160; At December 31, 2004, the
Company was hedging forecasted transactions for periods not exceeding fifteen
months and expects substantially all amounts reported in accumulated other
comprehensive earnings (losses) to be reclassified to the consolidated
statement of earnings within the next twelve months.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Derivative gains or losses
reported in accumulated other comprehensive earnings (losses) are a result of
qualifying hedging activity.&#160; Transfers
of gains or losses from accumulated other comprehensive earnings (losses) to
earnings are offset by corresponding gains or losses on the underlying hedged
item.&#160; Hedging activity affected
accumulated other comprehensive earnings (losses), net of income taxes, during
the years ended December 31, 2004, 2003 and 2002, as follows (in millions):</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.5in;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Credit
exposure and credit risk</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company is exposed to
credit loss in the event of nonperformance by counterparties.&#160; However, the Company does not anticipate
nonperformance, and such exposure was not material at December 31, 2004.</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">39</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='39',FILE='C:\JMS\smani\05-2188-6\task287381\2188-6-mm-05.htm',USER='smani',CD='Jan 31 15:15 2005' -->


<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div style="font-family:Times New Roman;">

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .25in;text-indent:-.25in;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Fair value</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .25in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The aggregate fair value,
based on market quotes, of the Company&#146;s third-party debt at December 31, 2004,
was $12,835 million as compared with its carrying value of $12,291
million.&#160; The aggregate fair value of the
Company&#146;s third-party debt at December 31, 2003, was $13,426 million as
compared with its carrying value of $12,919 million.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">See Notes 4, 8 and 9 for
additional disclosures of fair value for short-term borrowings and long-term
debt.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><u><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Note
18.&#160; Contingencies</font></u>:</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Kraft and its subsidiaries
are parties to a variety of legal proceedings arising out of the normal course
of business, including a few cases in which substantial amounts of damages are
sought.&#160; While the results of litigation
cannot be predicted with certainty, management believes that the final outcome
of these proceedings will not have a material adverse effect on the Company&#146;s
consolidated financial position, results of operations or cash flows.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 45.0pt;text-indent:-.5in;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Third-Party Guarantees</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 45.0pt;text-indent:-.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">At December 31, 2004, the Company&#146;s third-party
guarantees, which are primarily derived from acquisition and divestiture
activities, approximated $25 million.&#160;
Substantially all of these guarantees expire through 2013, with $1
million expiring during 2005.&#160; The
Company is required to perform under these guarantees in the event that a third
party fails to make contractual payments or achieve performance measures.&#160; The Company has a liability of $20 million on
its consolidated balance sheet at December 31, 2004, relating to these
guarantees.</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">40</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>

  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="10%" colspan="2" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:10.0%;">
  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:2.0%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="10%" colspan="2" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:10.0%;">
  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:2.0%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="10%" colspan="2" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:10.0%;">
  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

</head>

<body lang="EN-US">

<div>

<p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">EXHIBIT 99.2</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><u><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">REPORT OF MANAGEMENT ON INTERNAL CONTROL OVER FINANCIAL REPORTING</font></u></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="color:black;line-height:normal;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;text-indent:0in;"><font size="2" color="black" face="Times New Roman" style="color:windowtext;font-size:10.0pt;">Management
of Kraft Foods Inc. is responsible for establishing and maintaining adequate
internal control over financial reporting as defined in Rules 13a-15(f) and
15d-15(f) under the Securities Exchange Act of 1934.&#160; Kraft Foods Inc.&#146;s internal control over
financial reporting is a process designed to provide reasonable assurance
regarding the reliability of financial reporting and the preparation of
financial statements for external purposes in accordance with accounting
principles generally accepted in the United States of America.&#160; The Company&#146;s internal control over financial
reporting includes those written policies and procedures that:</font></p>

<p style="color:black;line-height:normal;margin:0in 0in .0001pt 9.0pt;text-autospace:none;text-indent:0in;"><font size="2" color="black" face="Times New Roman" style="color:windowtext;font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="color:black;font-size:10.0pt;line-height:normal;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-autospace:none;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="3" color="black" face="Times New Roman" style="color:windowtext;font-size:12.0pt;">&#149;</font><font size="1" color="black" face="Times New Roman" style="color:windowtext;font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font><font color="black" face="Times New Roman" style="color:windowtext;">pertain to the maintenance of records that, in reasonable
detail, accurately and fairly reflect the transactions and dispositions of the
assets of Kraft Foods Inc.;</font></p>

<p style="color:black;line-height:normal;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-autospace:none;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" color="black" face="Times New Roman" style="color:windowtext;font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="color:black;font-size:10.0pt;line-height:normal;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-autospace:none;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="3" color="black" face="Times New Roman" style="color:windowtext;font-size:12.0pt;">&#149;</font><font size="1" color="black" face="Times New Roman" style="color:windowtext;font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font><font color="black" face="Times New Roman" style="color:windowtext;">provide reasonable assurance that transactions are recorded
as necessary to permit preparation of financial statements in accordance with
accounting principles generally accepted in the United States of America;</font></p>

<p style="color:black;line-height:normal;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-autospace:none;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" color="black" face="Times New Roman" style="color:windowtext;font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="color:black;font-size:10.0pt;line-height:normal;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-autospace:none;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="3" color="black" face="Times New Roman" style="color:windowtext;font-size:12.0pt;">&#149;</font><font size="1" color="black" face="Times New Roman" style="color:windowtext;font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font><font color="black" face="Times New Roman" style="color:windowtext;">provide reasonable assurance that receipts and expenditures
of Kraft Foods Inc. are being made only in accordance with authorizations of
management and directors of Kraft Foods Inc.;&#160;
and</font></p>

<p style="color:black;line-height:normal;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-autospace:none;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" color="black" face="Times New Roman" style="color:windowtext;font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="color:black;font-size:10.0pt;line-height:normal;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-autospace:none;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="3" color="black" face="Times New Roman" style="color:windowtext;font-size:12.0pt;">&#149;</font><font size="1" color="black" face="Times New Roman" style="color:windowtext;font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font><font color="black" face="Times New Roman" style="color:windowtext;">provide reasonable assurance regarding prevention or timely
detection of unauthorized acquisition, use or disposition of assets that could
have a material effect on the consolidated financial statements.</font></p>

<p style="color:black;line-height:normal;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-autospace:none;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" color="black" face="Times New Roman" style="color:windowtext;font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="color:black;line-height:normal;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;text-indent:0in;"><font size="2" color="black" face="Times New Roman" style="color:windowtext;font-size:10.0pt;">Internal
control over financial reporting includes the controls themselves, monitoring
and internal auditing practices and actions taken to correct deficiencies as
identified.</font></p>

<p style="color:black;line-height:normal;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;text-indent:0in;"><font size="2" color="black" face="Times New Roman" style="color:windowtext;font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="color:black;line-height:normal;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;text-indent:0in;"><font size="2" color="black" face="Times New Roman" style="color:windowtext;font-size:10.0pt;">Because
of its inherent limitations, internal control over financial reporting may not
prevent or detect misstatements.&#160; Also,
projections of any evaluation of effectiveness to future periods are subject to
the</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='',FILE='C:\JMS\dhaile\05-2188-6\task288135\2188-6-mo.htm',USER='dhailea',CD='Jan 31 17:59 2005' -->


<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div>

<p style="color:black;line-height:normal;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;text-indent:0in;"><font size="2" color="black" face="Times New Roman" style="color:windowtext;font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="color:black;line-height:normal;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;text-indent:0in;"><font size="2" color="black" face="Times New Roman" style="color:windowtext;font-size:10.0pt;">risk
that controls may become inadequate because of changes in conditions, or that
the degree of compliance with the policies or procedures may deteriorate.</font></p>

<p style="color:black;line-height:normal;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;text-indent:0in;"><font size="2" color="black" face="Times New Roman" style="color:windowtext;font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="color:black;line-height:normal;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;text-indent:0in;"><font size="2" color="black" face="Times New Roman" style="color:windowtext;font-size:10.0pt;">Management
assessed the effectiveness of Kraft Foods Inc.&#146;s internal control over
financial reporting as of December 31, 2004.&#160;
Management based this assessment on criteria for effective internal
control over financial reporting described in <i><font style="font-style:italic;">Internal
Control - Integrated Framework</font></i> issued by the Committee of Sponsoring
Organizations of the Treadway Commission (&#147;COSO&#148;).&#160; Management&#146;s assessment included an
evaluation of the design of the Company&#146;s internal control over financial
reporting and testing of the operational effectiveness of the Company&#146;s
internal control over financial reporting.&#160;
Management reviewed the results of its assessment with the Audit
Committee of our Board of Directors.</font></p>

<p style="color:black;line-height:normal;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;text-indent:0in;"><font size="2" color="black" face="Times New Roman" style="color:windowtext;font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="color:black;line-height:normal;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;text-indent:0in;"><font size="2" color="black" face="Times New Roman" style="color:windowtext;font-size:10.0pt;">Based
on this assessment, management determined that, as of December 31, 2004, Kraft
Foods Inc. maintained effective internal control over financial reporting.</font></p>

<p style="color:black;line-height:normal;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;text-indent:0in;"><font size="2" color="black" face="Times New Roman" style="color:windowtext;font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="color:black;line-height:normal;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;text-indent:0in;"><font size="2" color="black" face="Times New Roman" style="color:windowtext;font-size:10.0pt;">PricewaterhouseCoopers
LLP, independent registered public accounting firm, who audited and reported on
the consolidated financial statements of Kraft Foods Inc. included in this
report, has issued an attestation report on management&#146;s assessment of internal
control over financial reporting.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>
